I"¶<p>When <em>Nginx</em> serves HTTPS on another port than <em>443</em>, it returns a 400 error when not requested as <strong><code class="highlighter-rouge">https://</code></strong><code class="highlighter-rouge">example.com:8888</code> explicitly:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p><strong><code class="highlighter-rouge">400 Bad Request</code></strong> <code class="highlighter-rouge">The plain HTTP request was sent to HTTPS port</code></p>
</blockquote>

<p>To redirect to https on that port automatically, add this <code class="highlighter-rouge">error_page</code> directive to the <em>Nginx</em> server configuration:</p>
<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>error_page 497 =301 https://$http_host$request_uri;
</code></pre></div></div>

